9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 41, L.D. 77, “An Act to Stabilize and
10 Sustainably Fund the Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife, Fisheries and
11 Hatcheries Division by Increasing the Inland Fishing License Fees and Establishing the
12 Inland Fisheries Conservation and Enhancement Fund”
13 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
14 'An Act to Stabilize and Sustainably Fund the Department of Inland Fisheries and
15 Wildlife, Fisheries and Hatcheries Division by Increasing the Inland Fishing License
16 Fees and Establishing the Inland Fisheries Conservation and Enhancement Program'
17 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
18 following:
19 'Sec. 1. 12 MRSA §10108, sub-§13 is enacted to read:
20 13. Inland Fisheries Conservation and Enhancement Program. The Inland
21 Fisheries Conservation and Enhancement Program, referred to in this subsection as “the
22 program,” is established within the department's fisheries and hatcheries division.
23 A. The program must:
24 (1) Prioritize native inland fish conservation and the research, management and
25 enhancement of the State's native fish, including but not limited to those identified
26 by the department as species of greatest conservation need, brook trout, lake
27 whitefish, arctic charr and lake trout;
28 (2) Identify and implement actions to enhance native fish production and stocking,
29 including assessment of native fish production programs; and
30 (3) Continue to conserve, protect and enhance the State's sport fish fisheries.
31 B. To the extent that resources allow, the program must also support and incorporate
32 the following elements:
Page 1 - 132LR0251(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 41, L.D. 77
1 (1) The design and implementation of regional and statewide fisheries research
2 programs to conserve the State's native inland and sport fish fisheries, ensuring the
3 long-term sustainability and health of the State's fisheries;
4 (2) Investment in new technology, equipment and training programs to enhance
5 the success and effectiveness of the program;
6 (3) Effective communication regarding ongoing program actions, success and
7 collaboration;
8 (4) The establishment of collaborative partnerships to engage organizations,
9 communities and companies representing conservation groups, anglers, land trusts
10 and other organizations involved in outdoor recreation in implementing and
11 publicizing the program; and
12 (5) Engagement with representatives of various agencies, anglers and nonprofit
13 organizations to enhance and restore the State's native fisheries habitat and
14 populations.
15 C. The commissioner may accept money, goods or services donated to the department
16 for the program. Money accepted by the commissioner under this subsection must be
17 deposited into the fisheries and hatcheries division dedicated account.
18 D. The commissioner, or the commissioner's designee, shall report no later than
19 February 1st annually to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having
20 jurisdiction over inland fisheries and wildlife matters regarding program activities,
21 emphasizing the work being done to conserve, research, manage and enhance the
22 State's native inland fish populations and including a summary of expenditures and
23 their allocation.
24 Sec. 2. 12 MRSA §10252, as affected by PL 2003, c. 614, §9 and amended by c.
25 655, Pt. B, §51 and affected by §422, is repealed and the following enacted in its place:
26 §10252. Fish hatchery maintenance fund
27 1. Fund established. The fish hatchery maintenance fund, referred to in this section
28 as "the fund," is established in the department as a nonlapsing fund to be used by the
29 commissioner to fund or assist in funding engineering designs, statewide facilities
30 assessments and maintenance, repair and capital improvements at fish hatcheries and
31 feeding stations owned by the State. The fund may be used for overtime personnel services
32 costs when overtime for fish stocking and other hatchery-related work is operationally
33 required. Additionally, the fund may support the design, construction and operation of
34 additional state fish hatcheries that support the mission of the department, as approved by
35 the Legislature. The fund may not be used to fund the general operating costs of an existing
36 fish hatchery.
37 2. Funding. Notwithstanding section 10801, subsection 4, $2 from each fishing
38 license sold must be deposited into the fund. Additionally, money deposited pursuant to
39 Title 29-A, section 456-C, subsection 3, paragraph A, subparagraph (1) must also be
40 credited to the fund. The commissioner may accept and deposit into the fund any monetary
41 gifts, donations or other contributions from public or private sources and must use that
42 money for the purposes specified in subsection 1.
